			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				[*ahem* this will be my 3 (count 'em, 3) cp as it is quite early in the morning in preparation to have 4 impacted wisdom teeth extracted, at which point all I'll be able to do in EQ, is sit on my rump, click my macros, and haggle; and while having some hearty ol' oatmeal.]<BR>
<BR>
(this part may be duly ignored by those who can better spend their lives, although that is doubtful as you are on an EQ spoiler site, oh well)<BR>
<BR>
Originally, I had an extreme distaste to this game as anyone I knew who has played has destroyed their lives over this game, the reason at which this query was replied to as &quot;so my character can look cool.&quot; Add to that, I heard tell that it was Sony's attempt to warp the world of J.R.R. Tolkien known as Middle-Earth, a rumor of which I thought to be heresy and dribble since no substantial congress of people can truly interpret the imagination of a single individual. Third, whenever my colleagues wanted to show off their &quot;uber phat lewt, yo!&quot;, almost all of the text that I read was that of mindlessly stupid genoicidal tendencies and superiority complexes. (Mind you, this only directly shows the nature of a few members of the community of Everquest and is not intended to represent any general congregation of players.) In short, I thought it was stupid.<BR>
<BR>
(this part may be ignored even more than the part before it!)<BR>
<BR>
However, with the arrival of PvP servers of infinitely more difficulty than any of the &quot;blue&quot; servers, I began to become intrigued as to why in Zebuxorux's name this game still existed. So, on the suggestion of a hitherto nameless player who sells his accounts on ebay bi-monthly for actual monetary profit, I made a gnome necromancer. Needless to say, it was a long time before I took up the game again.<BR>
<BR>
(please use '/ignore', have a nice day!)<BR>
<BR>
Then, everyone started saying Luclin and Lord of the Rings movie, and it annoyed the FlippyDarkpaw out of me. So, I decided to take up the game once more and try out the [forbidden in almost all RL European Lore] monk class. For some reason, dunno why, I actually had fun. Then someone told me that Instill Doubt takes forever to increase with out 41 skill points. This was enough to cause me to stop playing yet again. Except this time, the game had performed an Instill Doubt on me. (Whoever didn't see that coming, please perform '/smack' on yourself 100 million times. You know you want to.)<BR>
<BR>
(Just scroll down to the bottom, if you even want to bother reading this tripe anymore.)<BR>
<BR>
Then, someone told me dwarves could somersault on some servers. It was this mere fact, amongst all the doubts I had in my mind (should I see how Verant screwed up Tolkien's writing form, why not play some other game instead, etc., etc.?) that actually got me to play with consistency. As a newbie dwarven rogue, I was an audience to some quite quirky and entertaining stories of in-game newbie quests. Then some guy I knew wanted to start a High Elf Paladin while his RL g/f started a High Elf Enchanter. I then proceeded to not care about my monk and rogue, and go on their server as a totally untwinked wood elf warrior, just to see if I can outdo a minor-twinked charac in overall performance. (He was lvl 12, I was lvl 10, I slaughtered him until he died, and then I killed him again while smashed [drunk to tunnel vision].)<BR>
<BR>
(Now, this is the actually 2cp, everything above is just 1cp, but I'll trade it to you for a Fine Steel Morning Star.)<BR>
<BR>
Now, from what I've skimmed of Banegrivm Shadowblight's 'research' the vast majority of the text looks like it's breaking copyright law with the master site itself, http://sony.evequest.com, and the pictures of the books are just outright insult to the very people he's endorsing, 'the questers'. (Gotta earn those books from doing the right quests, right?) The last 2 topics have been argued so many times that I'm developing a migraine; as any devoted history teacher knows, you don't force history into students, you encourage interest in it. (After all, doesn't everyone want to know the history of George W. Bush, C average student of Yale University? C'mon, three cheers for the silly ol' chum!) So, from what I understand, this guy is either lecturing or reading straight off the book. At this point, I would like to recommend that he get a certified US government document allowing him at least to tutor history, that way he'll have an even larger audience to lecture to! (WOOT! I mean, uh, CVXB! I mean, uh, ding?)<BR>
<BR>
(Now for the dramatic conclusion!)<BR>
<BR>
If you really want story that can't be obtainable by your class/race/deity, just go on sony. Besides, you know you want to spam Mennix, the handsome halfling. Do it, or 'smack yourself on the head!' again. Either way, it's a win-win situation.<BR>
<BR>
(Wow, so much of what I said will be of no real significance in altering the future of the world.... wait wasn't that J.R.R. Tolkien's subliminal message?)<BR>
<BR>
You have gotten better at Fishing! (1)
